03784nam a22005415i 9780804777377DE-B159720200915044058.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||200915t20202010cau    fo  d z      eng d  a97808047773777 a10.1515/97808047773772doi  a(DE-B1597)563600  a(OCoLC)1198931752  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  acaucUS-CA 4aPN56.H55bH687 7aLIT0041302bisacsh04a809.894a809.93358405318a809/.933584053181 aHorsman, Yasco, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aTheaters of Justice :bJudging, Staging, and Working Through in Arendt, Brecht, and Delbo /cYasco Horsman. 1aStanford, CA : bStanford University Press, c[2020] 4cÂ©2010  a1 online resource (232 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aCultural Memory in the Present00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: Coming to Terms with the Past: Trial, Therapy, and the Theater -- t1. Arendt's Laughter: Theatricality, Pedagogy, and Comedy in Eichmann in Jerusalem -- t2. Founding a Nation, Healing a Wound: On Crimes against Humanity -- t3. A Cry for Justice: Charlotte Delbo's Auschwitz and After and Days and Memory -- t4. Brecht on Trial: The Courtroom, the Theater, and The Measures Taken -- tConclusion: Judging, Staging, and Working Through -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tCultural Memory in the Present 0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWhat role do legal trials have in collective processes of coming to terms with a history of mass violence? How does the theatrical structure of a criminal trial facilitate and limit national processes of healing and learning from the past? This study begins with the widely publicized, historic trials of three Nazi war criminals, Eichmann, Barbie, and Priebke, whose explicit goal was not only to punish, but also to establish an officially sanctioned version of the past. The Truth and Reconciliation commissions in South America and South Africa added a therapeutic goal, acting on the belief that a trial can help bring about a moment of closure. Horsman challenges this belief by reading works that reflect on the relations among pedagogy, therapy, and legal trials. Philosopher Hannah Arendt, poet Charlotte Delbo, and dramaturg Bertolt Brecht all produced responses to historic trials that reopened the cases those trials sought to close, bringing to center stage aspects that had escaped the confines of their legal frameworks.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 15. Sep 2020) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 0aJustice in literature. 0aPsychoanalysis and literature. 0aTrials in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / European / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertSUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311070420440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978080477737740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780804777377423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780804777377.jpg  a978-3-11-070420-4  SUP Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013c2000d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles